The paper deals with the problem of attributing a model's prediction to its base features and extends the notion of attribution to feature interactions. This is a common problem in machine learning and falls under the category of "Machine Learning" (cs.LG). The paper proposes a new method called the Shapley-Taylor index, which is a generalization of the Shapley value. This method is applicable to a wide range of models and can be used to identify interesting qualitative insights. Therefore, the paper can also be classified under "Artificial Intelligence" (cs.AI). The paper also discusses the use of the Shapley-Taylor index in three different models, which involves data analysis and manipulation. Hence, it can be classified under "Data Structures and Algorithms" (cs.DS), "Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science" (cs.CE), and "Information Theory" (cs.IT).
